  "prompt": "Videos: What is the file size per hour of recording 720p of video?",
  "response": "The file size of a video recording at 720p resolution per hour depends on several factors, including the **bitrate**, **codec**, **frame rate**, and **compression settings**. Here's a general estimate:\n\n### 720p Video File Size Per Hour:\n1. **Average Bitrate**:\n   - **H.264 Codec** (commonly used):\n     - Low quality: ~1,000 kbps (kilobits per second) \u2192 ~450 MB per hour\n     - Medium quality: ~2,500 kbps \u2192 ~1.1 GB per hour\n     - High quality: ~5,000 kbps \u2192 ~2.25 GB per hour\n   - **H.265 Codec** (more efficient, smaller file sizes):\n     - Similar quality to H.264 but up to **50% smaller file sizes**.\n\n2. **File Size Formula**:\n   \\[\n   \\text{File Size (MB)} = \\frac{\\text{Bitrate (kbps)} \\times \\text{Duration (seconds)}}{8,000}\n   \\]\n   Example: For 2,500 kbps for 1 hour (3,600 seconds):\n   \\[\n   \\text{File Size} = \\frac{2,500 \\times 3,600}{8,000} = 1,125 \\text{ MB} \\approx 1.1 \\text{ GB}\n   \\]\n\n### Key Factors Affecting File Size:\n- **Bitrate**: Higher bitrate = larger file size.\n- **Codec**: H.265 (HEVC) is more efficient than H.264.\n- **Frame Rate**: Higher frame rates (like 60 fps instead of 30 fps) increase file size.\n- **Compression**: Better compression reduces file size but may affect quality.\n\nFor **720p**, the file size typically ranges from **450 MB to 2.5 GB per hour**, depending on the settings.",
